A rogue "DHCP" server causes it to Offer IP leases to hosts, which can be misconfigured. Misconfigured settings such as; Incorrect Subnet Masks, wrong default gateway and wrong DNS server can cause connectivity issues.


To fix this problem, Use ZENMAP to scan IPs












Scan DHCP queries
After opening zenmap, run the syntax shown in the picture in the command box (target may vary based on what subnet ur in)
Notice how there are 2 different responses coming from different IP addresses.
To know which one is rogue. On devices with connectivity issues, run:
ipconfig /all
Compare their responses with devices that have correct network settings.
















Disable or block the rogue DHCP server
If possible, go to the rogue machine (physical or virtual, e.g., Hyper-V) and turn it off.
Alternatively, create a packet filtering rule to block/deny the rogue IP/MAC address from the network. 







Verify network is clean
Run the nmap --script=dhcp-discover scan again to confirm only the legitimate DHCP server responds.

(The image shows 2 queries coming from the same IP address meaning that the rogue device is removed) 













Renew IP addresses on affected devices
On devices that received the wrong DHCP lease, run:
ipconfig /release
ipconfig /renew
this ensures they get proper IP configurations from the authorized DHCP server.

